1. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) - The paper discusses a distinguisher attack on a homomorphic encryption scheme, which falls under the domain of cryptography and security. 
2. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper uses error-correcting codes, which is a topic in information theory. 
3. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The attack described in the paper involves computing the dimension of a punctured square code, which could potentially involve computational complexity. 
4. cs.CY (Computers and Society) - The paper discusses the security implications of a homomorphic encryption scheme, which could be relevant to the societal impact of computer technology. 
5. cs.SE (Software Engineering) - The paper proposes an attack on a specific software implementation of a homomorphic encryption scheme, which could be relevant to software engineering.
